WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:01.560
I guess I just had a thought.

00:01.560 --> 00:03.880
I kind of answered it for myself here.

00:03.880 --> 00:06.520
But we put in those dev tools, so we put in the React

00:06.520 --> 00:08.200
and the 10-stack dev tools.

00:08.200 --> 00:09.080
And I was curious.

00:09.080 --> 00:10.920
My question to myself was, hey, can I

00:10.920 --> 00:13.000
inspect that call just there?

00:13.000 --> 00:14.160
And I absolutely can.

00:14.160 --> 00:16.200
But I'm wondering if, I guess maybe this

00:16.200 --> 00:19.120
is general for now or later, if there

00:19.120 --> 00:22.600
are any common uses you have of those dev tools.

00:22.600 --> 00:24.880
I think we put them in there, and I haven't really

00:24.880 --> 00:25.800
touched them since.

00:25.800 --> 00:27.080
Yep.

00:27.080 --> 00:29.960
So to your good point here, you can

00:29.960 --> 00:33.120
click the 10-stack query dev tools down here.

00:33.120 --> 00:35.120
You'll see both queries and mutations up here.

00:35.120 --> 00:38.560
You can see our query mutation right there.

00:38.560 --> 00:40.280
This is just helpful for me to see,

00:40.280 --> 00:42.320
did it happen and what data got sent?

00:42.320 --> 00:44.880
That's 95% of my question.

00:44.880 --> 00:47.680
The other thing, I could definitely just look at the network tab

00:47.680 --> 00:50.600
and see what happened there.

00:50.600 --> 00:52.640
But it's nice that it's here.

00:52.640 --> 00:56.180
I can see everything, like what happened, what came back,

00:56.180 --> 00:58.760
how many things were subscribed to it,

00:58.760 --> 01:03.360
what kind of event triggered it, all that kind of stuff.

01:03.360 --> 01:08.080
So do I need to see, is it cancelable all the time?

01:08.080 --> 01:09.920
No, probably not.

01:09.920 --> 01:14.920
Or probably never is probably closer to what I would say.

01:14.920 --> 01:16.120
But it's cool that it's there.

01:16.120 --> 01:17.560
And there are input validations.

01:17.560 --> 01:20.320
Should we be using uncontrolled forms?

01:20.320 --> 01:22.580
Not necessarily.

01:22.580 --> 01:25.240
It depends on how you want to do it.

01:25.240 --> 01:31.120
So first of all, the browser already has some built into it.

01:31.120 --> 01:34.040
So if I just do this, it's going to say,

01:34.040 --> 01:37.080
please enter an email address.

01:37.080 --> 01:38.720
That's from Firefox, right?

01:38.720 --> 01:40.160
That's not from anything.

01:40.160 --> 01:42.040
That's just from Firefox saying, this

01:42.040 --> 01:43.880
isn't at least remotely approaching

01:43.880 --> 01:45.880
a valid email address.

01:45.880 --> 01:47.000
It's pretty loose, right?

01:47.000 --> 01:50.520
So it will still allow some pretty weird things through.

01:50.520 --> 01:52.160
It probably will let that go.

01:52.160 --> 01:53.260
It didn't, right?

01:53.260 --> 01:57.700
And that's obviously not a valid email address.

01:57.700 --> 02:00.340
But if you were trying to do a valid date of birth,

02:00.340 --> 02:01.720
and you want to make sure that it's

02:01.720 --> 02:07.700
like within the past 150 years or something like that,

02:07.700 --> 02:11.380
I still probably would do that on submit.

02:11.380 --> 02:12.180
And why?

02:12.180 --> 02:15.940
Because I don't want, I hate, it's a huge pet peeve of mine.

02:15.940 --> 02:19.500
If I start typing my birthday, which is like 05,

02:19.500 --> 02:21.660
and then it turns red and it's like, oh, enter

02:21.660 --> 02:22.660
a valid birthday.

02:22.660 --> 02:24.860
I'm not done yet.

02:24.860 --> 02:26.740
Stop telling me that I don't have a valid,

02:26.740 --> 02:28.020
because I'm working on it.

02:28.020 --> 02:31.420
And so that's why I don't like using a controlled input,

02:31.420 --> 02:32.960
because it would immediately show you

02:32.960 --> 02:34.460
that something is wrong, right?

02:34.460 --> 02:36.620
When in reality, you want to show them at the end,

02:36.620 --> 02:38.460
it's like, no, actually you have to be born

02:38.460 --> 02:40.700
within the past 150 years for this to be valid.

02:43.420 --> 02:49.540
You would do that on submit, not on key down, right?

02:49.540 --> 02:53.620
So still I would use, I would do uncontrolled for that,

02:53.620 --> 02:56.500
and then just do it on the submit where I would do that.

03:00.820 --> 03:03.020
I don't know, there's probably other reasons as well.

03:03.020 --> 03:06.500
In my page, it has fields which has dependencies

03:06.500 --> 03:09.180
on other fields, for instance, state and city.

03:09.180 --> 03:11.220
For that, should we use controlled forms?

03:11.220 --> 03:12.980
Yeah, that's a really good place to do it.

03:12.980 --> 03:18.140
So let's say you put zip code, right?

03:18.140 --> 03:20.660
And for example, in my old zip code in Seattle,

03:20.660 --> 03:22.500
you could see this that you live in Seattle,

03:22.500 --> 03:25.460
or you could say you live in Greenwood.

03:25.460 --> 03:28.740
Both are technically valid places.

03:28.740 --> 03:31.580
And you would show that probably in a dropdown.

03:31.580 --> 03:34.540
And you would do that based on zip code, which

03:34.540 --> 03:37.300
wouldn't be populated until they put their zip code in.

03:37.300 --> 03:40.740
You would use a controlled input for that.

03:44.100 --> 03:47.400
I'm not telling you to do great, terrible things

03:47.400 --> 03:52.080
to avoid using controlled inputs,

03:52.080 --> 03:54.560
but just mostly that they're not necessary for things

03:54.560 --> 04:01.320
of this nature, where this is an extremely normal looking form.

04:01.320 --> 04:04.920
And therefore, it's very valid to just not have

04:04.920 --> 04:06.640
to do anything controlled about it.

04:12.200 --> 04:14.040
Cool.

04:14.040 --> 04:17.200
Again, we didn't hit any errors.

04:17.200 --> 04:20.800
Let's say that we hit like a 500, or what is it?

04:20.800 --> 04:25.800
437, I am a teapot error, something like that.

04:25.800 --> 04:30.160
But inside of post-contact, this response

04:30.160 --> 04:34.680
was not OK, which is basically anything that's under 400.

04:34.680 --> 04:38.000
It would throw the error here.

04:38.000 --> 04:43.360
And then inside of contact, we would get a flag here

04:43.360 --> 04:47.400
from 10-stack query.

04:47.400 --> 04:53.720
And you could do something like if, where is it?

04:53.720 --> 04:57.000
Mutation.isError.

04:57.000 --> 04:58.560
And you can see there's a bunch of them.

04:58.560 --> 05:01.920
IsPending, isPause, isIdle, isSuccess, blah, blah, blah.

05:01.920 --> 05:06.720
But if error, you can just return something, again,

05:06.720 --> 05:09.760
very customer friendly, like, well, no, something

05:09.760 --> 05:10.560
like that, right?

05:13.800 --> 05:17.160
And that's how you'd handle errors in their posts.

05:17.160 --> 05:18.160
Yeah, Mark?

05:18.160 --> 05:22.120
Is there a case where you'd use both uncontrolled forms

05:22.120 --> 05:24.560
but controlled input?

05:24.560 --> 05:32.640
Yeah, I mean, you can kind of see that I do that in order.

05:37.080 --> 05:40.320
So if you look here, we have this whole form.

05:40.320 --> 05:44.920
But I'm handling all of the data on submit.

05:44.920 --> 05:46.920
And then where am I taking that data?

05:46.920 --> 05:48.560
So this is a set card.

05:48.560 --> 05:51.560
So I guess I'm just doing this directly with the things

05:51.560 --> 05:52.840
that I have set in state.

05:52.840 --> 05:54.760
But there's no reason that I couldn't have just

05:54.760 --> 06:01.440
done something like const form data equals new form data,

06:01.440 --> 06:05.440
right, and done it the exact same way.

06:05.440 --> 06:06.560
Both are fine.

06:06.560 --> 06:08.400
At this point, you're kind of splitting hairs

06:08.400 --> 06:10.240
of what's controlled and what's uncontrolled

06:10.240 --> 06:12.560
to really the answer is it doesn't really matter, right?

06:12.560 --> 06:14.160
Just write the code that looks the best.

06:16.440 --> 06:17.760
But sure, yeah, there's certainly

06:17.760 --> 06:21.640
you're going to have things where some of the inputs

06:21.640 --> 06:22.560
will be controlled.

06:22.560 --> 06:23.800
Some of them will not be controlled.

06:23.800 --> 06:25.520
And you'll get it all off the form data.

06:25.520 --> 06:28.720
That would make sense to me.

06:28.720 --> 06:31.880
It's not a binary thing where either it's all controlled

06:31.880 --> 06:33.160
or all uncontrolled.

06:33.160 --> 06:33.840
You can do both.

